{"title":"‘Hello, World’","link":"https://twitter.com/MIT_CSAIL/status/1363875135191678984","date":1614135025000,"content":"<div id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"><section aria-labelledby=\"accessible-list-0\" role=\"region\"><h2 aria-level=\"1\" dir=\"auto\" role=\"heading\" id=\"accessible-list-0\">Conversation</h2><div aria-label=\"Timeline: Conversation\"><div><article role=\"article\" data-focusable=\"true\" tabindex=\"0\"><div><div data-testid=\"tweet\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/MIT_CSAIL\" role=\"link\" data-focusable=\"true\"><div aria-label=\"\"><p><img alt=\"\" draggable=\"true\" src=\"https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/885505956272115712/U81HpDxb_normal.jpg\"></p></div></a></div><div><div><p><span>Today’s the day that “hello world” said “hello world!” The term was coined in a textbook published </span><span><a dir=\"ltr\" href=\"https://twitter.com/hashtag/otd?src=hashtag_click\" role=\"link\" data-focusable=\"true\">#otd</a></span><span> in 1978: “C Programming Language,” written by Brian Kernighan and Dennis Ritchie. </span><a dir=\"ltr\" href=\"https://t.co/1Lv0pyEho2?amp=1\" target=\"_blank\" role=\"link\" data-focusable=\"true\" rel=\" noopener noreferrer\">go.aws/37TmOZq</a><span> </span><span><a dir=\"ltr\" href=\"https://twitter.com/hashtag/tdih?src=hashtag_click\" role=\"link\" data-focusable=\"true\">#tdih</a></span><span> </span><span><a dir=\"ltr\" href=\"https://twitter.com/hashtag/helloworld?src=hashtag_click\" role=\"link\" data-focusable=\"true\">#helloworld</a></span></p></div><div><a href=\"https://twitter.com/MIT_CSAIL/status/1363875135191678984/photo/1\" role=\"link\" data-focusable=\"true\"><div aria-label=\"Image\" data-testid=\"tweetPhoto\"><p><img alt=\"Image\" draggable=\"true\" src=\"https://pbs.twimg.com/media/Eu11B_ZXcAMaejv?format=png&amp;name=small\"></p></div></a></div></div></div></article></div><div><article role=\"article\" data-focusable=\"true\" tabindex=\"0\"><div data-testid=\"tweet\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/jeffbigham\" role=\"link\" data-focusable=\"true\"><div aria-label=\"\"><p><img alt=\"\" draggable=\"true\" src=\"https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/1355009540320858113/nH3CQ1rw_normal.jpg\"></p></div></a></div></article></div><div><article role=\"article\" data-focusable=\"true\" tabindex=\"0\"><div data-testid=\"tweet\"><div><a href=\"https://twitter.com/cryo2go\" role=\"link\" data-focusable=\"true\"><div aria-label=\"\"><p><img alt=\"\" draggable=\"true\" src=\"https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/1340104586988826628/lwHoMdzb_normal.jpg\"></p></div></a></div><div><p><span>for my info: it is not just about describing a scene, alt text should also be provided for images of text, s.t. electronic readers don't mangle things?</span></p></div></div></article></div><div><article role=\"article\" data-focusable=\"true\" tabindex=\"0\"><div data-testid=\"tweet\"><div><a href=\"https://twitter.com/bmjames\" role=\"link\" data-focusable=\"true\"><div aria-label=\"\"><p><img alt=\"\" draggable=\"true\" src=\"https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/53147827/pantsman_normal.jpg\"></p></div></a></div><div><p><span>I wouldn't say the book \"coined\" the term. It may have popularised it. To \"coin\" a term surely you have to be the first to use it. There is evidence of \"hello world\" programs being written years before this book. The wording of the book implies this too.</span></p></div></div></article></div><div><article role=\"article\" data-focusable=\"true\" tabindex=\"0\"><div data-testid=\"tweet\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/SamWibatt\" role=\"link\" data-focusable=\"true\"><div aria-label=\"\"><p><img alt=\"\" draggable=\"true\" src=\"https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/1302665114735181824/Qp4E9rTr_normal.png\"></p></div></a></div></article></div><div><article role=\"article\" data-focusable=\"true\" tabindex=\"0\"><div data-testid=\"tweet\"><div><a href=\"https://twitter.com/lifengtian\" role=\"link\" data-focusable=\"true\"><div aria-label=\"\"><p><img alt=\"\" draggable=\"true\" src=\"https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/1253122771569250304/jHrd-44k_normal.jpg\"></p></div></a></div><div><p><span>\"its use as a test phrase is widely believed to have begun with Brian Kernigham’s 1972 book, A Tutorial Introduction to the Language B.\"</span></p></div></div></article></div><div><article role=\"article\" data-focusable=\"true\" tabindex=\"0\"><div data-testid=\"tweet\"><div><a href=\"https://twitter.com/lifengtian\" role=\"link\" data-focusable=\"true\"><div aria-label=\"\"><p><img alt=\"\" draggable=\"true\" src=\"https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/1253122771569250304/jHrd-44k_normal.jpg\"></p></div></a></div><div><p><span>‘Brian Kernigham‘ should be 'Brian Kernighan'</span></p></div></div></article></div><div><article role=\"article\" data-focusable=\"true\" tabindex=\"0\"><div data-testid=\"tweet\"><div><a href=\"https://twitter.com/vasudevram\" role=\"link\" data-focusable=\"true\"><div aria-label=\"\"><p><img alt=\"\" draggable=\"true\" src=\"https://pbs.twimg.com/profile_images/831115122/indian-bison-gaur_normal.jpg\"></p></div></a></div><div><p><span>IIRC, I read somewhere that the Hello World program tradition originated before C. Maybe with the languages B or BCPL, which were C's predecessors. In fact, that may be corroborated by something I seem to remember from the K&amp;R C book: they say something like ...</span></p></div></div></article></div></div></section></div>","author":"John Gruber","siteTitle":"Daring Fireball","siteHash":"fc569638025dadf22a867470f8215f38855cf50e975782a6c989909474292a36","entryHash":"009525eb58d0bbfc7ad6b051343e7fca88cc0dabc52f8a605f2dbd2e64ebfefe","category":"Tech"}